WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:19.000
A trip to Bavaria. Going abroad.

00:19.000 --> 00:25.000
Pete, Josephine is talking to you. Our daughter, remember?

00:25.000 --> 00:28.000
Yes, dear. No, sugar. Thank you.

00:28.000 --> 00:32.000
What? She's trying to tell you something.

00:32.000 --> 00:34.000
Oh, what's the point?

00:34.000 --> 00:37.000
Her name is Heidi. She lives near Munich.

00:37.000 --> 00:42.000
Oh, that's nice. That's where the doctor burfest takes place.

00:42.000 --> 00:45.000
Don't you mean the Oktoberfest?

00:45.000 --> 00:51.000
That's what I said, Nancy. Lots of lovely, strong German men drinking beer.

00:51.000 --> 00:55.000
I don't see what that's got to do with Josie's trip to Germany.

00:55.000 --> 01:00.000
Anyway, Josie, try making contact with your father again, please.

01:00.000 --> 01:03.000
Put Heidi's photo in front of his nose.

01:03.000 --> 01:06.000
Dad. No more toast. Thank you.

01:06.000 --> 01:10.000
Look at this. She's nice, isn't she?

01:10.000 --> 01:13.000
Very nice. A friend of yours.

01:13.000 --> 01:18.000
Her name's Heidi. She's German. I'm going to visit her in Germany.

01:18.000 --> 01:19.000
Nice.

01:19.000 --> 01:22.000
Did you hear what Josie said?

01:22.000 --> 01:25.000
And put that newspaper down.

01:25.000 --> 01:29.000
We want to have a real conversation with you.

01:29.000 --> 01:32.000
Oh, there's more life in a plastic bag.

01:32.000 --> 01:40.000
But Josie is going to stay with her German exchange partner near Munich for two months in the summer holidays.

01:40.000 --> 01:45.000
Well, that's nice. Wait a minute. Munich?

01:45.000 --> 01:47.000
That's in Germany.

01:47.000 --> 01:50.000
At the last, welcome back to our planet.

01:50.000 --> 01:52.000
Give me up, Scotty.

01:52.000 --> 01:57.000
Oh, who is Scotty? I once had a budget called Scotty.

01:57.000 --> 02:00.000
He was very clever. He could speak.

02:00.000 --> 02:05.000
I taught him to say, close the window. Close the window.

02:05.000 --> 02:09.000
One day I forgot, and he flew out the window.

02:09.000 --> 02:11.000
Be quiet, please, Mum.

02:11.000 --> 02:13.000
Germany?

02:13.000 --> 02:17.000
Yes, Germany. Munich is in Germany.

02:17.000 --> 02:19.000
But...

02:19.000 --> 02:21.000
There are Germans in Germany.

02:21.000 --> 02:26.000
Your knowledge of European geography is very impressive. You should be on mastermind.

02:26.000 --> 02:31.000
Yes, Dad. There are lots of Germans in Germany.

02:31.000 --> 02:34.000
I'm going to stay with a German family for two months.

02:34.000 --> 02:38.000
But... but... they speak German.

02:38.000 --> 02:42.000
Gosh, is there no limit to my husband's intelligence?

02:42.000 --> 02:46.000
Why don't you go to a nice country, a sensible country?

02:46.000 --> 02:48.000
What do you suggest, dearest?

02:48.000 --> 02:55.000
Well, America, or Canada, or even... Gibraltar.

02:55.000 --> 03:00.000
I want to improve my German, Dad. All those countries speak English.

03:00.000 --> 03:06.000
Yes, but why do you want to learn another language? Everyone speaks English.

03:06.000 --> 03:09.000
I'm learning German at school, remember?

03:09.000 --> 03:13.000
I went to Germany once. I didn't know that.

03:13.000 --> 03:14.000
When?

03:14.000 --> 03:16.000
When the Kaiser was still alive.

03:16.000 --> 03:20.000
I'm not sure when it was a long time ago.

03:20.000 --> 03:25.000
I think it was Germany. Or maybe it was the Isle of Wight.

03:25.000 --> 03:33.000
It looked very foreign, lots of bicycles and hills, and people with sunglasses and red faces.

03:33.000 --> 03:36.000
Anyway, Mum says I can go to Germany.

03:36.000 --> 03:39.000
It's with the school. Nothing can happen.

03:39.000 --> 03:46.000
I know. We can come and visit you. We can have a holiday in Germany too.

03:46.000 --> 03:50.000
Not so fast, Mum. I don't think Josie was.

03:50.000 --> 03:56.000
That's awesome. Yes, that's a great idea. Why not come near the end?

03:56.000 --> 04:02.000
And then we can visit some places together. What a good idea. Don't you think so, Pete?

04:03.000 --> 04:05.000
You can meet Heidi and her father.

04:05.000 --> 04:12.000
That's settled then. We're coming. Perhaps Heidi's father can find us a cheap hotel for a few days.

04:12.000 --> 04:17.000
Cool. I can get Heidi to ask her father. I'm sure he knows some places.

04:17.000 --> 04:25.000
A trip to Germany. How exciting. It's our first trip abroad for over 15 years.

04:25.000 --> 04:29.000
No, it's not. We went to Calais two years ago.

04:29.000 --> 04:35.000
That's not exactly true. You forgot your passport and we couldn't enter France.

04:35.000 --> 04:39.000
All we saw was the port from the ferry and then we came back again.

04:39.000 --> 04:47.000
Yes, I forgot. Why did you marry him, Nancy? I liked Andrew. He sells vacuum cleans.

04:47.000 --> 04:53.000
I met his wife. She left him in January. Now she lives with the ice cream man.

04:53.000 --> 04:58.000
Andrew's alone at home with his hovers. You too.

04:58.000 --> 05:05.000
Josie, what present are you taking? What about a book of jokes? You know Germans have no sense of humour.

05:05.000 --> 05:09.000
Don't be stupid, Dad. Maybe a towel. Sorry?

05:09.000 --> 05:16.000
It's a fact that on holidays Germans always get up early in the morning to put their towels on the sunbeds next to the pool.

05:16.000 --> 05:21.000
Don't listen to your father. He lives in his own fantasy world of stereotypes.

05:21.000 --> 05:29.000
Perhaps some typical English food. You know things like tea and marmite and food.

05:29.000 --> 05:35.000
That's a great idea, Grand. Josie, make sure you don't mention the war.

05:35.000 --> 05:39.000
Stop it, Pete. We're in the European Union now.

05:39.000 --> 05:45.000
I'm not. I never wanted to join. Right. Come on Boris. Walkies.

05:45.000 --> 05:49.000
Let's go and breathe some good English air together.

05:50.000 --> 05:55.000
Oh dear. I'm not so sure it's a good idea to take Dad to Germany, Mum.

05:55.000 --> 06:01.000
Yes, I know. But he doesn't really mean what he says. He's just trying to be funny.

06:01.000 --> 06:09.000
But he never says anything that is funny. No. I know. Sad really, isn't it?

06:10.000 --> 06:12.000
Mmm.

06:16.000 --> 06:18.000
Bavaria, here we come.

06:20.000 --> 06:29.000
Why didn't we fly? This ferry journey is so boring. And Port Boris is locked in the car. I hope he's alright.

06:29.000 --> 06:36.000
Of course he is. It's nice to go by ferry. A real sense of adventure.

06:36.000 --> 06:45.000
We English are famous for RC captains. So Walter Raleigh. Captain Cook.

06:47.000 --> 06:51.000
Christopher Columbus. Christopher Columbus was Italian.

06:51.000 --> 06:56.000
Don't be ridiculous, Italian. He can't be Italian.

06:56.000 --> 07:01.000
What are the Italians given the world besides pizza and ice cream?

07:01.000 --> 07:04.000
I think Mum's right, Pete.

07:04.000 --> 07:11.000
No, anyway. Sir Francis Chichester, the first man to sail around the world alone.

07:11.000 --> 07:18.000
All right. All right, you made your point. Anyway, not long now, I hope.

07:22.000 --> 07:31.000
And please, Josie is having such a nice time with the family. I'm really looking forward to seeing her again and meeting the family. Aren't you?

07:31.000 --> 07:33.000
Yes, but...

07:35.000 --> 07:43.000
Oh, it's so exciting. It makes me feel tipsy. Everything is going from side to side.

07:43.000 --> 07:49.000
The sea is very rough. I don't like it too much. Oh, my stomach.

07:49.000 --> 07:54.000
It's very nice of Heidi's father to say we can stay in his house.

07:54.000 --> 07:59.000
Yes, it is. The Germans are such nice people, don't you agree, Pete?

07:59.000 --> 08:04.000
What's the name of Josie's German family? Her Fokker?

08:04.000 --> 08:08.000
What's his first name? And where's Mrs Fokker?

08:08.000 --> 08:19.000
I don't know his Christian name. Germans are much more formal, Pete. I read it in the guidebook. I don't know where Heidi's mother is. Maybe they're divorced.

08:19.000 --> 08:26.000
I wouldn't be surprised with a name like that. I wonder if he fought in the war. I must ask him.

08:26.000 --> 08:35.000
Please don't. Anyway, he isn't old enough. Don't forget that the war finished over 60 years ago.

08:35.000 --> 08:43.000
I don't feel too well. My stomach doesn't like it. Oh, my stomach.

08:43.000 --> 08:50.000
Don't worry. It's okay. Here. Have a peanut butter sandwich. They taste great.

08:50.000 --> 08:53.000
Here are some chocolate biscuits too.

08:54.000 --> 08:58.000
No, I can't eat anything.

08:58.000 --> 09:02.000
Don't be there. Don't worry. Do you want some coke?

09:02.000 --> 09:05.000
No, thank you. I just want to sit quietly.

09:05.000 --> 09:08.000
Shall I get you an ice cream?

09:08.000 --> 09:12.000
I want to go up on deck. Smell the sea air.

09:12.000 --> 09:16.000
Don't fall overboard. See you later.

09:17.000 --> 09:24.000
See you later. Why didn't we fly, Pete? I feel awful.

09:24.000 --> 09:26.000
Another sandwich, dear.

09:26.000 --> 09:31.000
Enjoy the exhibit. Can it isn't Stulham? What?

09:31.000 --> 09:35.000
Are you all right? Do you have a speech problem?

09:35.000 --> 09:45.000
Enjoy the exhibit. Can't you speak a proper language?

09:46.000 --> 09:52.000
What did he want? I have no idea. He was speaking in a funny language.

09:52.000 --> 09:58.000
French, I think. It wasn't French. He spoke German. He's German.

09:58.000 --> 10:03.000
French, German. It's all the same.

10:03.000 --> 10:07.000
Pete, do you think it had a good idea to come by car?

10:07.000 --> 10:13.000
You know the problems we have with it. It's so old and it's not very reliable.

10:13.000 --> 10:21.000
I checked everything very carefully. I'm sure nothing can go wrong.

10:21.000 --> 10:26.000
Sorry. How long is the journey to Bavaria?

10:26.000 --> 10:29.000
Only a few hours. It's all motorway.

10:29.000 --> 10:32.000
You know they drive on the other side of the road.

10:32.000 --> 10:35.000
Are you all right? You don't look well.

10:35.000 --> 10:37.000
Of course I'm all right.

10:37.000 --> 10:42.000
Yes, I know they drive on the left. I'm not totally stupid.

10:42.000 --> 10:47.000
No dear. Of course you're not. It can't be difficult.

10:47.000 --> 10:50.000
Trust me.

10:50.000 --> 10:55.000
You look a bit green. Are you sure you're okay?

10:55.000 --> 11:01.000
Just a bit of indigestion. Oh, I think. Oh dear.

11:01.000 --> 11:05.000
I think I ate too many peanut butter sandwiches.

11:05.000 --> 11:11.000
I think I need to go to the toilet.

11:11.000 --> 11:15.000
I don't feel too well. Do you need some help?

11:15.000 --> 11:20.000
No, no dear. It's just a bit of indigestion.

11:20.000 --> 11:24.000
Oh, careful dear. The boat is swaying a lot.

11:24.000 --> 11:29.000
Sorry, madam. Sorry.

11:29.000 --> 11:34.000
Hello, Pete. Isn't it fun? Are you all right?

11:34.000 --> 11:39.000
Hello, Nancy. Pete looks as white as a sheet.

11:39.000 --> 11:43.000
Poor Lord Nelson is not feeling too well.

11:43.000 --> 11:49.000
Oh, that noise. Look, it's Pete. He fell over the table.

11:49.000 --> 11:56.000
Oh, where is he? Look, ma'am. The coast. I can see the coast.

11:56.000 --> 11:59.000
We're almost there. Where's Pete?

11:59.000 --> 12:02.000
We have to go downstairs to the car.

12:02.000 --> 12:06.000
I think that's him in the corner over there.

12:06.000 --> 12:10.000
Leave him for a few minutes. I think he's falling asleep.

12:10.000 --> 12:13.000
It's nice to have a bit of peace and quiet.

12:13.000 --> 12:15.000
We could leave him there, Nancy.

12:15.000 --> 12:20.000
What a terrible thought, ma'am. We can't do that.

12:20.000 --> 12:26.000
Can we? I suppose not. But it's a nice idea.

12:31.000 --> 12:33.000
On the road.

12:37.000 --> 12:40.000
What's the matter with these bloody Germans?

12:40.000 --> 12:44.000
They are crazy as the end of the world come.

12:44.000 --> 12:50.000
Look out. There's another one coming at supersonic speed.

12:50.000 --> 12:52.000
Be careful.

12:56.000 --> 12:59.000
Where the bloody hell did that one come from?

12:59.000 --> 13:03.000
Why do they drive so fast? It's dangerous.

13:03.000 --> 13:09.000
And why is every bloody German got either a bloody Mercedes or a bleeding BMW?

13:09.000 --> 13:11.000
Who won the war anyway?

13:11.000 --> 13:18.000
It's exciting. They all look such fun. Why can't we go any faster?

13:18.000 --> 13:23.000
I'm doing 55. This car wasn't built for speed.

13:26.000 --> 13:28.000
It wasn't built for comfort either.

13:28.000 --> 13:31.000
Or leg room. Or relaxation.

13:31.000 --> 13:34.000
All right. All right. Don't keep on.

13:39.000 --> 13:45.000
Everyone is laughing at us as they overtake. I don't see what's so funny.

13:45.000 --> 13:49.000
Maybe our orange and pink colour scheme has something to do with it.

13:49.000 --> 13:52.000
Everyone in Germany seems to have a black car.

13:52.000 --> 13:55.000
There's another car behind us, Pete.

13:55.000 --> 13:59.000
It's so close. I think it's climbed into our boot.

13:59.000 --> 14:01.000
Move over, Pete. Let him pass.

14:01.000 --> 14:06.000
I can't. There's only two lanes and the other is full of juggernauts.

14:06.000 --> 14:09.000
What's the speed limit on motorways?

14:09.000 --> 14:11.000
There isn't one in Germany.

14:11.000 --> 14:14.000
What? No speed limit. What fun?

14:14.000 --> 14:18.000
Come on, Pete. Faster. Faster.

14:18.000 --> 14:24.000
I can't go faster. Stop it, you silly old bag. Be quiet and sit down.

14:24.000 --> 14:28.000
There's a sign, Pete. 120.

14:28.000 --> 14:34.000
120. 120. A speed limit of 120 miles per hour.

14:34.000 --> 14:37.000
I would go into orbit if I went that fast.

14:37.000 --> 14:41.000
I don't think there's a chance of that happening in this car.

14:41.000 --> 14:44.000
Call me. Hello, Mr. Nice German man.

14:44.000 --> 14:46.000
What are you doing, Mum?

14:46.000 --> 14:51.000
I'm waving to the driver behind. Why doesn't he wave back?

14:52.000 --> 14:57.000
Oh, that's not very friendly. That's not nice at all.

14:57.000 --> 15:01.000
I would like to have a word with his mother. Teach him some manners.

15:04.000 --> 15:08.000
What are you doing, Mum? Stop here, Boris.

15:08.000 --> 15:11.000
Just showing him how we English do it.

15:11.000 --> 15:15.000
There. Take that. Stop that.

15:15.000 --> 15:19.000
Now, get your head back in the car and sit down.

15:22.000 --> 15:29.000
What are you doing in the bag? Why is the car flashing his lights?

15:29.000 --> 15:35.000
Mum's abusing the driver behind us. Silly thing to do. They're so reckless.

15:35.000 --> 15:39.000
I give up. I've had enough of this. That's enough.

15:39.000 --> 15:44.000
I'm going to pull over and leave the car on the motorway. We can walk the rest of the way.

15:44.000 --> 15:50.000
I think we all need a breather. And Boris needs a walk. Can we stop, Pete?

15:50.000 --> 15:56.000
All right, Nancy. I think that's a service station. All tight.

16:05.000 --> 16:10.000
I thought going on holiday was meant to be relaxing. A chance to unwind.

16:10.000 --> 16:16.000
If I see that man again, that's enough, Mum. Stop it.

16:16.000 --> 16:22.000
Can you give Boris a quick walk? All right, Nancy. Come on, Boris.

16:24.000 --> 16:28.000
Can we look at the map, please? It can't be far now.

16:28.000 --> 16:36.000
Now, we've passed Nürnberg. Here we are. Früchte. Whatever that means.

16:36.000 --> 16:40.000
What's the name of the town where Josie is staying?

16:40.000 --> 16:44.000
Here's a letter from here, Fokker. There's the address.

16:44.000 --> 16:52.000
Somewhere called... I can't read the beginning. His handwriting is not so easy to read.

16:52.000 --> 16:58.000
I think it's... Pafaf. Pafaf and Hoffen.

16:58.000 --> 17:03.000
Neither can I. Why are German words so long?

17:03.000 --> 17:09.000
English names are so much easier. Places like slough and redding and huster.

17:09.000 --> 17:13.000
They're easy to say, but I mean, look at this name.

17:13.000 --> 17:17.000
Brisson. What a ridiculous name for a town.

17:17.000 --> 17:23.000
Dear, I think you're looking at the wrong map. You're looking at a map of the Czech Republic.

17:23.000 --> 17:29.000
What? Ah, yes. Well, there's no difference. All these foreign names are stupid.

17:29.000 --> 17:35.000
I can't pronounce any of these places. It doesn't matter anyway. I know where.

17:36.000 --> 17:41.000
Let me have a look. Maybe I can read it.

17:41.000 --> 17:46.000
I don't think you can read it. I didn't know schools existed when you were young.

17:46.000 --> 17:51.000
Stop it, Pete. I bought a German washing machine many years ago.

17:51.000 --> 17:58.000
So? The instruction book was in German. Did you understand it, Mum? No.

17:58.000 --> 18:04.000
So why? It doesn't matter. I found this place on the map yesterday.

18:04.000 --> 18:11.000
It's near Munich. Yes. Ah, here. South of Ingold. Whatever it's called.

18:11.000 --> 18:15.000
Are you sure it's right? It doesn't look the same.

18:15.000 --> 18:19.000
Of course I'm right. Come on. It's not far now.

18:35.000 --> 18:43.000
We've just passed Ingold's, whatever it's called, give Josie a ring on our mobile and she can give us directions.

18:43.000 --> 18:46.000
That's a good idea.

18:51.000 --> 19:02.000
Josie, is that you? It's me, Mum. How are you? We're fine. Dad's a bit stressed with the driving.

19:02.000 --> 19:09.000
No, I'm not. It's you two in the back who was stressing me. Ask how I get to her house.

19:09.000 --> 19:14.000
I'm leaving the motorway at the next junction and it is sign posted to her town.

19:14.000 --> 19:23.000
Did you hear that, Josie? Good. Uh-huh, yes. All right.

19:24.000 --> 19:34.000
Second left opposite the church. Large white gates. House number 32. Right. Thank you, love.

19:34.000 --> 19:38.000
With you in a few minutes. Bye.

19:41.000 --> 19:44.000
Finding the right address.

19:46.000 --> 19:51.000
Look out for the church, everyone. We should see it soon. Stop!

19:53.000 --> 20:01.000
What? Where? There! It's lovely. It's wearing short leather trousers.

20:01.000 --> 20:07.000
Stop it, mother. Your mother gets worse as she gets older. There's the church over there.

20:07.000 --> 20:14.000
Oh, that was easy to find. Drive slowly, Pete. It's the house opposite. Do you think that's it?

20:14.000 --> 20:21.000
It's got white gates, but it looks a bit strange and I can't see a house number.

20:21.000 --> 20:24.000
Huh? It must be the right one. Come on.

20:35.000 --> 20:43.000
It's Wilkone's stop-sogger coffin. Good afternoon. I'm Mrs. Britain. We're here to see Josie.

20:43.000 --> 20:50.000
It's Wilkone's stop-sogger coffin. It's most about the rules. Good? Uh, yes? What's he talking about?

20:50.000 --> 20:54.000
I don't know. Why is he talking through the letterbox?

20:54.000 --> 21:01.000
Can you open the door, please? We would like to see Josie, our daughter.

21:01.000 --> 21:07.000
It's Wilkone's stop-sogger coffin. I think we might be at the wrong house.

21:07.000 --> 21:13.000
What makes you think that? Come on. Back to the car and this time I'll phone Josie.

21:13.000 --> 21:20.000
Women have no idea about finding places. Typical. What a holiday.

21:30.000 --> 21:42.000
Where are you? What? We're here. Outside the church. Sorry? You're outside the church, too.

21:42.000 --> 21:47.000
We can't see you. And you can't see us. Perhaps we're in the wrong place.

21:47.000 --> 21:51.000
Of course we're in the wrong place. Even I can see that.

21:51.000 --> 21:55.000
You said you knew where Josie was staying. I thought I did.

21:55.000 --> 22:00.000
But obviously you didn't. Yes, I did. But just be quiet, please.

22:00.000 --> 22:09.000
I'm trying to find out where Josie is. Sorry, Josie. Yes. I have the map open. Yes.

22:10.000 --> 22:21.000
Yes. Oh. Ah. Isn't it the same place? Oh. Okay. Yes. Yes.

22:21.000 --> 22:29.000
Well? Josie is staying in Hunter Pafacthan and Hoefan, or some of the name like that.

22:29.000 --> 22:32.000
Yes, I know. It's here at the top of Mr. Fokker's letter.

22:32.000 --> 22:40.000
Apparently we're not in Hunter Pafacthan and Hoefan at the moment. We're in Pafacthan and Hoefan.

22:40.000 --> 22:45.000
They aren't the same place. It's an easy mistake to make. Anyone can make it.

22:45.000 --> 22:51.000
But the two names are completely different, Pete. Why didn't you let me look at the map?

22:51.000 --> 22:58.000
How much further is it? Not many miles. Just the other side of Munich. Come on.

23:03.000 --> 23:11.000
There she is. It's Josie. Cooey. Over there, Pete. Yes. Yes. I can see her.

23:14.000 --> 23:22.000
We're Josie. Hello. Hello. Come on. Take the car up the drive, Dad.

23:23.000 --> 23:35.000
It's a wonderful house. I told you it was big. Wow. It's bigger than Belgium.

23:35.000 --> 23:42.000
How many people live here? Just Heidi and her father. Oh yes. There's a housekeeper as well.

23:42.000 --> 23:49.000
She lives upstairs. What does Heidi's father do? Import drugs. Sell illegal weapons.

23:50.000 --> 23:56.000
Don't be so nasty. He's an English teacher. He's very nice. You'll like him.

23:56.000 --> 24:03.000
Put the car over there, Dad. A teacher. An English teacher. But it's German.

24:03.000 --> 24:10.000
How can he be an English teacher? Germans can't speak English. The Orvis-Vin in the end.

24:11.000 --> 24:15.000
I don't think this holiday is going to be much fun.

24:19.000 --> 24:21.000
Meeting the fuckers.

24:26.000 --> 24:35.000
And you must be Heidi. Nice to meet you. Guten Tag. I hope that is right.

24:35.000 --> 24:41.000
Hello Mrs. Britain. Yes, that is very good, Chairman. Nice to meet you too.

24:41.000 --> 24:48.000
Oh, please call me Nancy. Hello. Nice to meet you all. Come and meet my father.

24:48.000 --> 24:53.000
I'm looking forward to meeting him. Your father is single, isn't he?

24:53.000 --> 25:01.000
Don't get ideas. You're much too old. Yes. My mother died many years ago. I'm sorry.

25:01.000 --> 25:07.000
Look. There's my father. He's in the swimming pool. I'll go and tell him you are here.

25:07.000 --> 25:15.000
Come with me, Josie. And you just try and behave.

